	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">A fence represents a significant investment in your Stockton property—typically $5,000 to $15,000 or more. Understanding warranty coverage before you buy protects that investment and ensures you know exactly what to expect if problems arise. This guide explains the different types of fence warranties, what they typically cover, and how to make warranty claims.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>Types of Fence Warranties</h2>
	<p>Fence warranties come from two sources, each covering different aspects of your fence:</p>

	<h3>Material Warranties (Manufacturer)</h3>
	<p>These warranties come from the company that manufactures the fencing materials. They cover defects in the materials themselves—warping, cracking, discoloration, or premature deterioration not caused by improper installation or use.</p>

	<h3>Labor Warranties (Contractor)</h3>
	<p>These warranties come from the contractor who installs your fence. They cover workmanship issues—posts that lean, gates that don't close properly, panels that come loose, or other installation-related problems.</p>

	<h3>Why Both Matter</h3>
	<p>A material warranty won't help if poor installation causes failure, and a labor warranty won't cover defective materials. Ensure you have both types of protection for comprehensive coverage.</p>

	<h2>Material Warranty Comparison by Fence Type</h2>

